const a = [
  {"id":3514,"text":"A 4-year-old boy is brought by his parents with the complaint that he frequently catches a cold and gets cough. According to the parents, he had pneumonia thrice this year and had to be admitted to the hospital one time. On examination, an ejection systolic murmur is heard on the left upper sternal border with a fixed splitting of the second heart sound. The first heart sound is loud. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 298-299.","responses":[{"text":"Cystic fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3601,"text":"'Sign of 3' is a feature of which congenital disease of the heart?","explanation":"In **coarctation of the aorta**, classic radiographic findings can include a **\"3 sign\"** or \"figure 3 sign,\" which is due to pre- and post-stenotic dilatation of the aorta and indentation at the site of coarctation. This is often seen on a chest X-ray and can help in the diagnosis.\r\n\r\n\r\nTetralogy of Fallot is characterized on the chest X-ray as a \"boot-shaped\" heart, not the \"3 sign.\"\r\nPersistent truncus arteriosus involves a single arterial vessel coming out of the heart and does not produce a \"3 sign\" on imaging.\r\nAtrial septal defect and patent ductus arteriosus do have any specific radiographic findings.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 534.","responses":[{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Persistent truncus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3692,"text":"Which of the following pathologies is an indication for coronary artery bypass graft (CABG)?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 492.","responses":[{"text":"Valvular disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multivessel disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right-to-left shunt","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left-to-right shunt","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3892,"text":"Which vasculitis involves the aorta?","explanation":"**Takayasu disease**, also known as Takayasu arteritis, predominantly affects **large vessels**, including the **aorta and its main branches**. It is most commonly seen in young women and can lead to symptoms such as arm claudication, decreased pulses, and vascular bruits.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nPolyarteritis nodosa typically involves medium-sized arteries and does not generally affect the aorta.\r\n\r\nBehcet disease is a multisystem vasculitis but does not primarily involve the aorta.\r\n\r\nGiant cell arteritis affects large and medium-sized vessels, such as the temporal artery, but it generally does not involve the aorta.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 65.","responses":[{"text":"Behcet disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyarteritis nodosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Giant cell arteritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Takayasu disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3928,"text":"What is the length of nasogastric tube that should be inserted during gastric lavage?","explanation":null,"reference":"Vij K. Textbook of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology Principles and Practice. 5th ed. Elsevier; 2011: 450.","responses":[{"text":"50 cm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"30 cm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20 cm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"35 cm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"40 cm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3940,"text":"Which of the following should not be used as an antidote for sulphuric acid?","explanation":null,"reference":"PubChem. Sodium bicarbonate. Accessed June 21, 2022. https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/516892","responses":[{"text":"Magnesium oxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these can be used","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium bicarbonate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Milk of magnesia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Limewater","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3952,"text":"Which of the following blood vessels return blood from the body to the heart?","explanation":null,"reference":"About the heart and blood vessels - health encyclopedia - university of rochester medical center. Accessed June 19, 2022. https://www.urmc.rochester.edu/encyclopedia/content.aspx?ContentTypeID=90\u0026ContentID=P01761","responses":[{"text":"Left main coronary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aorta and superior vena cava","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aorta and pulmonary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary artery and inferior vena cava","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior vena cava and inferior vena cava","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":3961,"text":"Peripheral cyanosis occurs in which of the following pathologies?","explanation":"**Low cardiac output** can result in **peripheral cyanosis** due to inadequate blood circulation, causing a lack of oxygen supply to the extremities. When the body's tissues and organs do not receive enough oxygen, they may exhibit a bluish color, known as cyanosis.\r\n\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nCongenital heart diseases (right to left shunt condition would more likely result in central cyanosis, affecting areas like the lips and tongue, rather than peripheral cyanosis.\r\n\r\nPulmonary edema condition primarily affects lung function and would generally lead to central, not peripheral, cyanosis.\r\n\r\nPulmonary embolism would primarily affect lung function and would typically result in central, not peripheral, cyanosis.\r\n\r\nLung diseases would generally result in central cyanosis due to impaired gas exchange in the lungs, affecting the oxygen saturation of blood circulating to the central parts of the body.","reference":"Adeyinka A, Kondamudi NP. Cyanosis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 19, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482247/","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lung diseases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low cardiac output","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital heart diseases (right to left shunt)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4082,"text":"Which is the most common organism responsible for infective endocarditis?","explanation":"Overall, the most common organism responsible for infective endocarditis is ***Staphylococcus aureus***. Over recent years, Staphylococcus aureus has emerged as the leading cause of infective endocarditis, partly due to the increased use of intravascular devices and the prevalence of healthcare-associated infections.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n*Streptococcus viridans* was traditionally considered the most common cause, especially in cases associated with dental procedures leading to transient bacteremia; however, it is now more commonly associated with subacute forms of endocarditis.\r\n\r\n*Staphylococcus epidermidis* is more commonly associated with prosthetic valve endocarditis.\r\n\r\n*Enterococcus* species are a significant cause of infective endocarditis, particularly in healthcare settings and among older adults, but they are not the most common overall.\r\n\r\n*H. influenzae* is a less common cause of infective endocarditis and is more typically associated with cases in children and before the widespread use of the H. influenzae type b (Hib) vaccine.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nP.S. Different sources appear to contradict each other regarding the most common causative organism, with many saying *Streptococcus viridans* is the most common cause overall. We've cited the latest edition of Davidson here that says, \"Over three-quarters of cases are caused by streptococci or staphylococci. Viridans streptococci, such as *Streptococcus mitis* and *Strep. sanguis*, which are commensals in the oral cavity, can enter the bloodstream on chewing or tooth-brushing, or at the time of dental treatment, and are common causes of subacute endocarditis (Box 16.94)... *Staph. aureus* has now overtaken streptococci as the most common cause of acute endocarditis.\"\r\n\r\nThe question doesn't specify whether it's acute or subacute so it's hard to predict what the examiner is looking for. Our suggested answer based on the available information is *Staph. aureus*, but we cannot be 100% sure as we don't know if the question meant acute or subacute.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 528.","responses":[{"text":"Staphylococcus epidermidis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus viridans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"H. Influenzae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Entrococcus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4084,"text":"The exact spot where the QRS meets the ST-segment is known as:","explanation":null,"reference":"St segment - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 19, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/st-segment","responses":[{"text":"J-point","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"U-wave","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Osborne wave","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"QRS junction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"S-point","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4102,"text":"A term infant is born with a large ventricular septal defect. Which coronary heart disease is most commonly associated with ventricular septal defect?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 535.","responses":[{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transposition of great vessel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coarctation of Aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent ductus arteriosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4106,"text":"Which of the following is the hallmark feature of right sided heart failure?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 530.","responses":[{"text":"Enlarged Right ventricle on echocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericardial effusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiomegaly on chest X ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ankle and pretibial edema","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural effusion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4111,"text":"A colorless, odorless volatile liquid that may acquire a yellowish tinge on exposure to air, with burning sour taste are the physical and chemical properties of which mineral acid?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 482.","responses":[{"text":"Sulphuric acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxalic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrochloric acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbolic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4142,"text":"A 42-year-old man comes to the emergency department with a history of taking liquids for suicide purpose. His pulse rate is 92/min and blood pressure is 120 /70 mmhg. He also has ulceration around the mouth and tongue. His chest is full of crepts and has severely labored breathing. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","explanation":"In a case of suspected poisoning leading to severe respiratory distress and potential airway compromise, the primary objective is to stabilize the patient's vital functions. This includes **establishing and maintaining the airway**, **supporting breathing**, and **ensuring adequate circulation** (often referred to as **ABCs**). These basic life-supporting measures are of utmost importance and take precedence over other treatment modalities. In a case like this, the patient may require intubation or other advanced airway management techniques, supplemental oxygen, and possibly intravenous fluids and medications to support blood pressure and heart function.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nMouth wash and antacids may be helpful for treating the ulcerations around the mouth and tongue but do not address the primary life-threatening issues of airway compromise and respiratory distress. Maintaining blood pressure is important but is part of the 'C' in ABC and should not take precedence over airway and breathing. Injection morphine could potentially worsen respiratory depression and is not appropriate in this context. Airway maintenance alone does not address the need for ensuring adequate breathing and circulation.","reference":"Thim T, Krarup NHV, Grove EL, Rohde CV, Løfgren B. Initial assessment and treatment with the airway, breathing, circulation, disability, exposure (ABCDE) approach. International Journal of General Medicine. Published January 31, 2012. Accessed June 19, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3273374/","responses":[{"text":"Blood pressure maintenance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Injection morphine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Airway maintenance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Airway, breathing and circulation establishment","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mouth wash and antacids","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4146,"text":"Which type of atrial septal defect (ASD) is commonly associated with atrioventricular (AV) canal defect?","explanation":"**ASD primum** is commonly associated with **atrioventricular (AV) canal defects**. This is often seen in conditions like Down syndrome and is part of the spectrum of atrioventricular septal defects, which involve both the atrial and the ventricular septum as well as one or both of the AV valves.\r\n\r\nASD secundum is the most common type of ASD but is not specifically associated with AV canal defects. ASD sinus venosus and ASD coronary sinus are also specific types of ASD but are not commonly linked with AV canal defects.","reference":"Umapathi KK, Agasthi P. Atrioventricular canal defects. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 19, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557511/","responses":[{"text":"ASD primum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"ASD sinus venosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ASD coronary sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ASD secundum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4152,"text":"On autopsy, internal aspects of the stomach show brown folds and hardened esophagus. The acid involved will be:","explanation":null,"reference":"1. Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 487.\r\n2. Dow lecture slides: Cardiovascular module, Forensic slides, Topic: Corrosive poisoning 2","responses":[{"text":"Nicotinic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxalic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbolic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Salicylic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4157,"text":"A 25-year-old man complains of sharp pain which increases on lying down and is relieved with sitting. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":"**Pericarditis** is characterized by sharp chest pain that often worsens when lying down and improves upon sitting up or leaning forward. This pattern is due to the inflammation of the pericardial sac surrounding the heart.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nAortic dissection generally presents with severe, tearing pain that often radiates to the back. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) would be less likely to cause acute, sharp chest pain and is usually associated with long-term symptoms like shortness of breath and chronic cough. Both ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) and Non-ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI) would cause ischemic chest pain but generally would not have pain characteristics that change with position. They would also likely have other symptoms such as radiating pain, sweating, and palpitations.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 542.","responses":[{"text":"Pericarditis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic dissection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4181,"text":"The nutmeg liver in congestive cardiac failure has gross changes. Which of the following is the most likely correct answer?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 116.","responses":[{"text":"Red bluish areas in sinusoids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red brown pericentral zone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Red brown periportal zone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tan gray brown pericardial zone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pale yellow around central veins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4187,"text":"A 25-year-old patient with difficulty in breathing is diagnosed to have congestive heart failure. He is found to have differences in right and left arm pulses, diminished femoral pulses and notching of ribs on X-ray. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Coarctation of the aorta** is characterized by a narrowing of the aorta and would account for the symptoms of congestive heart failure, as well as the **differences in arm pulses, diminished femoral pulses**, and **rib notching on X-ray**.\r\n\r\nTransposition of great vessels typically causes cyanotic disease in the newborn period and is unlikely to present in this age group.\r\n\r\nMitral valve stenosis primarily affects the left heart and does not usually cause differences in arm pulses or diminished femoral pulses. \r\n\r\nVentricular septal defect would not lead to diminished femoral pulses or differences in right and left arm pulses. \r\n\r\nTetralogy of Fallot, a cyanotic congenital heart disease, would have been likely diagnosed much earlier in life and also does not typically present with rib notching or pulse differences between the arms.","reference":"1. Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 78.\r\n2. Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 509, 534.","responses":[{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transposition of great vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitral valve stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetralogy of Fallot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4229,"text":"A 50-year-old obese female complains about the shortness of breath after her trip to the USA. What is a possible diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sugerman HJ, Eklöf BG, Toff WD, Burke AE, Livingston EH. Air travel–related deep vein thrombosis and pulmonary embolism. JAMA. Published December 19, 2012. Accessed June 24, 2022. https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.2012.4098","responses":[{"text":"Pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tension pneumothorax","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastritis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4231,"text":"Which one of the following is considered as the principal preventive population strategy for cardiac disease?","explanation":null,"reference":"Yu E, Malik VS, Hu FB. Cardiovascular disease prevention by diet modification: jacc health promotion series. Journal of the American College of Cardiology. Published August 21, 2018. Accessed June 19, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6100800/","responses":[{"text":"Dietary \u0026 life style changes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stress management","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Safe cigarettes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adequate sleep","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adequate physical activity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4234,"text":"Atrial septal defect is:","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 533-535.","responses":[{"text":"A congenital, cyanotic defect between left and right atrium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A congenital, non-cyanotic defect between left and right ventricles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"An acquired defect of mitral valve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A congenital, non-cyanotic defect between left and right atrium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Defect between ascending aorta and pulmonary artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10204,"text":"Which of these is the most common association with a patent ductus arteriosus?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 535.","responses":[{"text":"Ventricular septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrial septal defect","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isolated","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Patent foramen ovale","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10205,"text":"What is the best method to prevent aspiration during gastric lavage in a comatose patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 515.","responses":[{"text":"Keeping the patient in a sitting position","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Use of endotracheal tube prior to the lavage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left lateral positioning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Keeping the head lower than the legs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10206,"text":"Which of these terms best describe angiography?","explanation":null,"reference":"Omeh DJ, Shlofmitz E. Angiography. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557477/","responses":[{"text":"An ionizing radiation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A diagnosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"An imaging technique","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"A surgical procedure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A drug","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10207,"text":"Which of these terms best describe echocardiography?","explanation":null,"reference":"Omerovic S, Jain A. Echocardiogram. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK558940/","responses":[{"text":"MRI of the heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT scan of the heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray of the heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eco of heart sounds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound of the heart","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10208,"text":"Which of these EKG changes are characteristic of atrial fibrillation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Nesheiwat Z, Goyal A, Jagtap M. Atrial fibrillation. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526072/","responses":[{"text":"Broad QRS complexes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absent P waves and regular R-R intervals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absent P waves and irregular R-R intervals","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Progressive lengthening of the PR interval","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saw tooth shaped P waves","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10209,"text":"What is the first step in the management of an unstable patient with atrial fibrillation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Nesheiwat Z, Goyal A, Jagtap M. Atrial fibrillation. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526072/","responses":[{"text":"IV fluids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV adenosine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV amiodarone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV nitrates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immediate DC cardioversion","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10210,"text":"What is the most common and serious side effect of nitrates?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 264.","responses":[{"text":"Xanthopsia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pruritus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tachycardia and arrythmia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Throbbing headache and postural hypotension","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperuricemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10211,"text":"Why are nitrates preferred sublingually instead of the oral route?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 264.","responses":[{"text":"To improve patient compliance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To improve duration of action","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To avoid cardiac circulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To avoid first pass metabolism","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"To avoid systemic side effects","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10212,"text":"Which antihypertensive has an initial hypertensive effect due to alpha 2 actions on the peripheral vasculature?","explanation":null,"reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 179-180.","responses":[{"text":"Methyldopa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atenolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clonidine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Phenoxybenzamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Captopril","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10213,"text":"A researcher wants to establish the prevalence of tuberculosis in Karachi. Which study design is most suitable for this?","explanation":"A **cross-sectional study** would be the most suitable study design for establishing the **prevalence of tuberculosis** in Karachi. This type of study is designed to assess the prevalence of a disease or condition in a specific population at a given point in time.\r\n\r\nCohort studies are usually forward-looking and are not the best to determine prevalence at a specific point. Case reports and case series are descriptive studies focused on single or multiple cases, but they do not provide a measure of prevalence. Case-control studies are retrospective and designed to identify factors associated with a disease, rather than determining its prevalence.","reference":"Jesson J. Cross-sectional studies in prescribing research. Published December 2001. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11722676/","responses":[{"text":"Cohort study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case report","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case control study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case series","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cross-sectional study","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10214,"text":"Which of these is the best modality to confirm the diagnosis of mitral stenosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"1) Bhandari S, Subramanyam K, Trehan N. Valvular heart disease: diagnosis and management. The Journal of the Association of Physicians of India. Published August 2007. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18019800/\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n2) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 519.","responses":[{"text":"Echocardiography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Clinical history","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"MRI scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chest X-ray","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10215,"text":"Which vasodilator drug is incorrectly paired with its mechanism of action?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Dilitiazem: Calcium channel blocker","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ivabradine: Sodium channel blocker","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isosorbide dinitrate: Increases cGMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metoprolol: Increases cAMP","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nicorandil: Opens potassium channels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10216,"text":"A 69-year-old man presents with chronic fatigue. He is a known cause of hypertension and a chest X-ray reveals bilateral pulmonary edema with a prominent left heart border. In line with this, what is the most appropriate description for his heart?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 552.","responses":[{"text":"Normal heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eccentric hypertrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Concentric hypertrophy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10218,"text":"What is the most important clinical finding in the diagnosis of congenital heart diseases?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ossa Galvis MM, Bhakta RT, Tarmahomed A, Mendez MD. Cyanotic heart disease. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 26, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK500001/","responses":[{"text":"Tachycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart murmur","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Central cyanosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tachypnea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peripheral cyanosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10219,"text":"Which of these drugs can cause gynecomastia?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Diazoxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydralazine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Guanathedine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reserpine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Eplerenone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10220,"text":"Which of these is the most common cause of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 569.","responses":[{"text":"Idiopathic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mutation involving sarcomere proteins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alcohol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mutation involving cytoskeletal proteins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10237,"text":"A 7-month-old infant presents with short stature. He is at the 5th percentile for both height and weight. On examination, his temperature is 102 degrees celsius, and he is also tachycardia and tachypneic. He has a history of recurrent infections but there is no complaint of diarrhea. What is the most likely underlying etiology?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Protein calorie malnutrition","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital heart disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congestive heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10238,"text":"In cardiothoracic bypass surgery, where does the blood go after passing through the venous reservoir?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Venous pump","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygenator","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic pump","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic cannula","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cell saver","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10251,"text":"What is the most common type of cardiomyopathy?","explanation":"**Dilated cardiomyopathy** is the most common type of cardiomyopathy. This form is characterized by enlargement and weakening of the heart's ventricular chambers, which can lead to heart failure and other complications.\r\n\r\nHypertrophic cardiomyopathy is the second most common and is characterized by thickening of the heart muscle, specifically the ventricular walls. Restrictive cardiomyopathy is the least common and involves the stiffening of the ventricular walls. Arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia is a rare form of cardiomyopathy that primarily affects the right ventricle and can cause arrhythmias. Unclassified cardiomyopathy includes those that do not fit into the other categories.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 568.","responses":[{"text":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Arrythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unclassified cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10252,"text":"A 56-year-old male presents with abdominal pain and peripheral edema. On examination, there is hepatomegaly as well as a positive shifting dullness. What are all these signs most indicative of?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Kidney failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malnutrition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right sided heart failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left sided heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary edema","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10253,"text":"Which of the following routes of administration is not used for nitroglycerin?","explanation":"**Intramuscular administration** is not a recommended or typical route for nitroglycerin delivery. Nitroglycerin is commonly used for acute angina and is designed for rapid onset of action, which is not achieved with intramuscular injection.\r\n\r\n**Lingual** and **buccal routes** are commonly used for fast-acting relief from angina symptoms. The **oral route** can be used for maintenance therapy, although it has a first-pass metabolism issue that limits its effectiveness. **Transdermal patches** are used for sustained-release nitroglycerin for prophylactic treatment.","reference":"Katzung BG, Todd W. Vanderah. Basic and Clinical Pharmacology. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 198.","responses":[{"text":"Buccal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transdermal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intramuscular","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingual","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10254,"text":"Which of the following drugs needs to be stopped if a woman is planning on conception?","explanation":"**Captopril** is an angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor and is **teratogenic**. It can cause renal dysplasia, oligohydramnios, and skull hypoplasia in the developing fetus. Therefore, it should be avoided in pregnant women or women planning to conceive.\r\n\r\n\r\nLabetalol, hydralazine, and methyldopa are considered relatively safer antihypertensive medications during pregnancy. Furosemide is a loop diuretic and is generally avoided in pregnancy due to its ability to decrease placental perfusion, but it is not as teratogenic as captopril.","reference":"Katzung BG, Todd W. Vanderah. Basic and Clinical Pharmacology. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 188-189.","responses":[{"text":"Labetalol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methyldopa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydralazine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Furosemide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Captopril","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10255,"text":"Which of these is the most important diagnostic sound in the diagnosis of mitral stenosis?","explanation":"A **mid-diastolic rumbling murmur** is characteristic of **mitral stenosis**. This murmur occurs due to the turbulent flow of blood across a stenotic mitral valve during diastole. This is most often heard best at the apex and may also be associated with an opening snap.\r\n\r\n\r\nA mid-systolic click is usually indicative of mitral valve prolapse, not stenosis. Soft S2 is not specific to mitral stenosis and can be found in various conditions. Loud S1 may be found in mitral stenosis, but it is not as diagnostic as a mid-diastolic rumbling murmur. Loud S2 is more indicative of pulmonary hypertension or aortic stenosis, not mitral stenosis.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 401.","responses":[{"text":"Mid diastolic rumbling murmur","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mid systolic click","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loud S2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loud S1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Soft S2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10256,"text":"A 30-year-old male presents to the office with a headache and heavy sweating. On examination, he is tachypneic and has increased blood pressure. What is the most likely cause?","explanation":"**Pheochromocytoma** is a catecholamine-secreting tumor that can cause **episodic or persistent hypertension**, **headache, sweating**, and **tachycardia**, which are the symptoms seen in the patient. This condition arises most commonly from chromaffin cells of the adrenal medulla.\r\n\r\nHypertension secondary to pituitary adenoma would not typically present with episodic symptoms like headache, sweating, and tachypnea. Hypertension secondary to renal disease usually presents more insidiously and is often asymptomatic in the early stages. Coarctation of the aorta could cause hypertension but would not account for the episodic symptoms like sweating and tachypnea. Hypertension secondary to adrenal cortex pathology would usually result from conditions like Cushing's syndrome or primary aldosteronism, which have different symptom profiles, like moon facies, buffalo hump, or low potassium levels, and would not usually present with episodic headaches and sweating.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1127.","responses":[{"text":"Hypertension secondary to pituitary adenoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pheochromocytoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension secondary to renal disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension secondary to adrenal cortex pathology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coarctation of aorta","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10257,"text":"Which of these organisms is involved in rheumatic fever?","explanation":"**Group A streptococci** are responsible for causing **streptococcal pharyngitis**, which if left untreated or inadequately treated, can lead to **rheumatic fever**. Rheumatic fever is an autoimmune response to the bacterial infection and can affect the heart, joints, skin, and nervous system.\r\n\r\nGroup B streptococci are generally associated with neonatal infections and are not involved in the pathogenesis of rheumatic fever. *Staph aureus* and *Staph epidermidis* are not implicated in rheumatic fever; they are more commonly associated with skin infections or endocarditis. *E. coli* is a Gram-negative bacterium that can cause gastrointestinal and urinary tract infections but is not associated with rheumatic fever.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 560-561.","responses":[{"text":"Group B streptococci","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Group A streptococci","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Staph aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"E coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staph epidermidis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10258,"text":"A 40-year-old male presents with complaints of increasing breathlessness, fatigue, and weakness for the last 2 months. He has a history of mediastinal Hodgkin lymphoma treated with radiation therapy 5 years ago. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Restrictive cardiomyopathy** can occur as a late complication of **radiation therapy**, especially in patients with mediastinal malignancies like Hodgkin lymphoma. The radiation can lead to fibrosis of the myocardium, resulting in impaired ventricular filling and symptoms like breathlessness, fatigue, and weakness.\r\n\r\nDilated cardiomyopathy generally does not have a strong association with radiation therapy and is more commonly idiopathic or related to genetic mutations. Myocarditis secondary to viral infection usually has a more acute presentation, often with fever, and may not relate to the history of Hodgkin lymphoma and radiation therapy. Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is generally a genetic disorder and does not relate well to the patient's medical history. Systolic heart failure is a broad term that describes a state rather than a specific type of heart disease; moreover, it does not specifically relate to the patient's history of radiation therapy.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 574.","responses":[{"text":"Myocarditis secondary to viral infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dilated cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systolic heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive cardiomyopathy","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10259,"text":"Which of these types of antidotes combine with poisons to form new less toxic compounds?","explanation":"**Chemical antidotes** work by chemically reacting with the poison to form a less toxic or non-toxic compound, thus **neutralizing** its harmful effects.\r\n\r\nPhysiological antidotes work by producing effects that are opposite to those of the poison but do not combine with the poison to form a new compound. Universal antidotes are general-purpose antidotes that can work against a variety of poisons but are generally not as effective as specific antidotes. Chelating agents bind to heavy metals in the body but do not form less toxic compounds with the poison. Physical antidotes work by adsorbing the poison or facilitating its elimination from the body without forming a new compound.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 475.","responses":[{"text":"Universal antidotes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemical antidotes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Physical antidotes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Physiological antidotes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chelating agents","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10260,"text":"Which anti-hypertensive drug is a short-acting agent that is given intravenously in hypertensive emergencies and works by releasing nitric oxide?","explanation":"**Sodium nitroprusside** is a short-acting agent that is administered intravenously (IV) for **hypertensive emergencies**. It works by releasing nitric oxide, leading to vasodilation and a rapid reduction in blood pressure.\r\n\r\n\r\nNifedipine is an oral calcium channel blocker and is not typically used for hypertensive emergencies. Esmolol is a short-acting beta-blocker used intravenously, but it does not work by releasing nitric oxide. Hydralazine is a vasodilator but is not the primary choice for hypertensive emergencies requiring rapid action via the intravenous route. Clonidine is an alpha-2 adrenergic agonist, also not used intravenously for hypertensive emergencies.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 514.","responses":[{"text":"Esmolol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nifedipine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clonidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium nitroprusside","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydralazine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10261,"text":"Which one of these is a modifiable risk factor for the prevention of cardiovascular diseases?","explanation":"**Obesity** is a **modifiable risk factor** for cardiovascular diseases, meaning it can be changed through lifestyle modifications such as diet and exercise. Weight loss has been shown to improve lipid profiles, reduce blood pressure, and decrease the risk of developing diabetes, all of which contribute to a lower risk of cardiovascular disease.\r\n\r\nFamily history, age, genetics, and gender are all non-modifiable risk factors for cardiovascular diseases. These factors cannot be changed through lifestyle modifications or medical interventions. Therefore, they do not serve as targets for preventive strategies aimed at reducing the risk of cardiovascular diseases.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 494.","responses":[{"text":"Age","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obesity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Family history","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Genetics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gender","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10262,"text":"Which of these is a non-modifiable risk factor in the context of cardiovascular diseases?","explanation":"**Family history** is a **non-modifiable risk factor** for cardiovascular diseases, meaning it cannot be changed through lifestyle modifications or medical interventions. A family history of cardiovascular disease indicates a genetic predisposition, which can increase one's risk but cannot be altered.\r\n\r\nHypertension, diabetes, smoking, and obesity are all modifiable risk factors for cardiovascular diseases. These factors can be managed or changed through lifestyle modifications, such as diet and exercise, and/or medical treatments. Therefore, they serve as targets for preventive strategies aimed at reducing the risk of cardiovascular diseases.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 494.","responses":[{"text":"Obesity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Family history","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Smoking","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diabetes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10263,"text":"Which of these EKG characteristics define a third-degree atrioventricular block?","explanation":"**Third-degree atrioventricular block**, also known as complete heart block, is characterized by **AV dissociation** and **ventricular escape rhythm**. In this condition, there is a complete lack of communication between the atria and ventricles. The atria and ventricles beat independently of each other, hence the term AV dissociation. Ventricular escape rhythms are a safety mechanism the heart employs to continue pumping blood when normal conduction pathways are disrupted.\r\n\r\nProgressive increase in PR interval is indicative of a first-degree AV block or Mobitz type I (Wenckebach) block, not a third-degree AV block. Saw tooth shaped P waves are a characteristic finding in atrial flutter. Though bradycardia can occur in third-degree AV block, broad QRS complexes are not specifically indicative of this condition and are more associated with bundle branch blocks or ventricular rhythms. Absent P waves are more indicative of atrial fibrillation or other atrial arrhythmias.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 410.","responses":[{"text":"Bradycardia with broad QRS complexes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"AV dissociation and ventricular escape rhythm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Progressive increase in PR interval","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saw tooth shaped P waves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Absent P waves","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10277,"text":"Which of these is the ideal position for performing a gastric lavage?","explanation":"The ideal position for performing a **gastric lavage** is the **left lateral position** as it helps in minimizing the risk of aspiration.\r\n\r\nA right lateral position is less ideal than the left lateral for gastric lavage because it may not allow for optimal drainage and could increase the risk of aspiration.\r\n  \r\nThe prone position would increase the risk of aspiration and is generally not used for gastric lavage.\r\n  \r\nFowler's is a sitting position that might be used in some medical settings, but it is not ideal for gastric lavage due to the risk of aspiration.\r\n  \r\nLying flat on the back (supine) could also increase the risk of aspiration, making it a non-ideal position for gastric lavage.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 516.","responses":[{"text":"Prone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Supine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Frowler's","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left lateral","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right lateral","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10392,"text":"Which of the following is incorrect regarding a stab wound?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 200, 201.","responses":[{"text":"In this injury bruising around the opening of the wound is seen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It may occur with a knife","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a wedge shaped opening wound","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It results from piercing with a pointed weapon","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Its greatest dimension is depth","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10401,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding age and color of a bruise?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 193.","responses":[{"text":"Blue on day 4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Green on day 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Yellow on day 7-12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal at 1 week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Depends on size and swelling","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11867,"text":"Which of the following is not a characteristic of an ideal homicidal poison?","explanation":null,"reference":"Cardiology module; Forensic-medicine lecture slides; Topic: General toxicology-I; Subtopic: Properties of an ideal homicidal poison.","responses":[{"text":"Cheap in price","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tasteless and odorless","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Should resemble a natural disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Easily available","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orally ingested","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11868,"text":"How many seconds does a normal PR interval last?","explanation":"The normal **PR interval** on an electrocardiogram (ECG) lasts between **0.12 to 0.20 seconds**, which is equivalent to 120 to 200 milliseconds. A prolonged PR interval may suggest a first-degree atrioventricular (AV) block or other forms of conduction abnormality.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 448.","responses":[{"text":"0.30 sec","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.22 sec","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.28 sec","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.20 sec","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"0.32 sec","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11869,"text":"What is malignant hypertension characterized by?","explanation":"**Malignant hypertension** is characterized by **hyperplastic arteriosclerosis**. This is a severe form of hypertension that is rapidly progressive and can result in organ damage if not promptly treated. Hyperplastic arteriosclerosis involves changes to the arterial wall, leading to narrowing of the lumen, which can cause reduced blood flow to organs, potentially leading to organ failure. Immediate medical intervention is required to manage malignant hypertension and its complications.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 490.","responses":[{"text":"Subluxation of cardiac vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyaline arteriosclerosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcific aortic stenosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic insufficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperplastic arteriosclerosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11870,"text":"What is the most common poison used to commit suicide in Pakistan?","explanation":"**Organophosphates** are often cited as a common poison used for **suicide** in Pakistan, particularly in rural areas where they are readily available as agricultural pesticides. These substances are highly toxic and act by inhibiting the activity of an enzyme called acetylcholinesterase, leading to accumulation of acetylcholine and causing severe symptoms that can be fatal if not treated promptly.\r\n\r\nAarsenic, barbiturates, kerosene oil, and potassium cyanide, are also toxic substances but are generally less accessible or less commonly used for this purpose in Pakistan.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh's Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 630.","responses":[{"text":"Organophosphates","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Barbiturates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kerosene oil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium cyanide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arsenic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11871,"text":"Digoxin is contraindicated in which of the following?","explanation":"Digoxin is contraindicated in **complete heart block**. This condition involves a blockage in the electrical conduction between the atria and ventricles, which can be further compromised by digoxin, potentially leading to severe bradycardia or asystole. \r\n\r\nDigoxin is not contraindicated in congenital disease, angina, hypertension, or congestive heart failure. In fact, it is often used as part of the treatment regimen for congestive heart failure to improve cardiac output.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 478.","responses":[{"text":"Complete heart block","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congestive heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Angina","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11872,"text":"What is the mechanism of action of milrinone?","explanation":"**Milrinone** inhibits **phosphodiesterase III**, leading to an increase in intracellular cyclic AMP (cAMP) levels, which in turn increases calcium ion influx into the cardiac myocytes. The end result is **enhanced myocardial contractility** and vasodilation. \r\n\r\nMilrinone is often used in the management of acute heart failure to improve cardiac output. It does not inhibit phosphodiesterase I, II, IV, or V.","reference":"Ayres JK, Maani CV. Milrinone. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 19, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532943/","responses":[{"text":"Inhibits phosphodiesterase V","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits phosphodiesterase II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits phosphodiesterase III","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits phosphodiesterase I","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits phosphodiesterase IV","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11873,"text":"What is the mechanism of action of losartan?","explanation":"**Losartan** is an angiotensin II receptor antagonist that selectively inhibits the binding of angiotensin II to the **AT1 receptor**, which is found in many tissues such as vascular smooth muscle and the adrenal glands. This blocking of AT1 receptors prevents angiotensin II from exerting its vasoconstrictive and aldosterone-secreting effects, thereby lowering blood pressure. It does not block AT2 receptors or have partial blocking effects on either type of receptor.","reference":"Mulla S, Siddiqui WJ. Losartan. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 19, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526065/","responses":[{"text":"Blocks partial AT2 receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blocks AT1 + AT2 receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blocks AT1 receptors","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blocks AT2 receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blocks partial AT1 receptors","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11874,"text":"Which of the following works by blocking VLDL synthesis?","explanation":"**Nicotinic acid (niacin)** works by blocking VLDL (very low-density lipoprotein) synthesis. It inhibits the release of free fatty acids from adipose tissue, leading to **reduced hepatic VLDL synthesis**. This action subsequently lowers LDL levels.\r\n\r\nStatin drugs work primarily by inhibiting the enzyme HMG-CoA reductase, which plays a central role in the production of cholesterol in the liver. Fibrates mainly reduce triglycerides and can increase HDL levels but do not primarily block VLDL synthesis. Neomycin is an antibiotic and does not have a lipid-lowering effect. Resins, such as bile acid sequestrants, work by binding to bile acids in the intestine, leading to the excretion of cholesterol, but they also do not directly block VLDL synthesis.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 293.","responses":[{"text":"Neomycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Resin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Statin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nicotinic acid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11875,"text":"Which of the following drugs is associated with myalgias and gallstones?","explanation":null,"reference":"Clofibrate. In: LiverTox: Clinical and Research Information on Drug-Induced Liver Injury. National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases; 2012. Accessed June 19, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK548134/","responses":[{"text":"Colestipol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biguanide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Statin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clofibrate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11876,"text":"Which of the following tests should be prescribed before starting a patient on statins?","explanation":"Before initiating **statin therapy**, it is recommended to check liver enzymes, including **alanine aminotransferase (ALT)** and **aspartate aminotransferase (AST)**, to establish a baseline and monitor for potential hepatotoxicity.\r\n\r\nUric acid is not directly related to statin therapy and is generally not monitored when prescribing statins. Blood urea nitrogen (BUN) is a marker for renal function and is also not typically checked before starting a patient on statins. Platelet count and red blood cell count are not specific tests needed before initiating statin therapy; they don't provide information on liver function, which is the primary concern with statins.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 376.","responses":[{"text":"ALT and AST","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Red blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"BUN","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uric acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11877,"text":"Which of the following drugs will you prescribe primarily to reduce triglycerides?","explanation":"**Fibrates** like fenofibrate and gemfibrozil are primarily used to lower high levels of triglycerides by activating **peroxisome proliferator-activated receptors (PPARs)**. \r\n\r\nIn contrast, ezetimibe is mainly used to lower LDL cholesterol and has a limited effect on triglycerides. Statins are predominantly aimed at lowering LDL cholesterol, although they can modestly reduce triglycerides. Nicotinic acid (niacin) is more often used for its ability to increase HDL levels, though it does have some triglyceride-lowering effects. Neomycin is an antibiotic and is not relevant to the management of lipid levels.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 377.","responses":[{"text":"Ezetimibe","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Statin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neomycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nicotinic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11878,"text":"Volition (delay of gratification) is the measure of which of the following?","explanation":"**Volition**, often demonstrated by the delay of gratification, is a measure of one's **willpower or self-control**. It reflects the ability to make choices that align with one's goals, even in the face of immediate temptation.\r\n\r\nBehavior is a broader term that encompasses a wide range of actions, not just those related to willpower. Thought refers to cognitive processes and does not specifically measure willpower. Self-awareness involves a conscious knowledge of one's own character and feelings but is not a measure of willpower. Action simply denotes doing something and also doesn't specifically indicate willpower.","reference":"Volition definition \u0026 meaning | britannica dictionary. Accessed June 21, 2022. https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/volition","responses":[{"text":"Thought","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self-awareness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Action","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Willpower","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Behaviour","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11879,"text":"Which antiarrhythmic drug causes systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)-like reaction?","explanation":"**Procainamide** is known to cause a **drug-induced systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)-like syndrome** in some patients. This is characterized by antinuclear antibodies and symptoms such as joint pain, which can mimic SLE.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 132.","responses":[{"text":"Flecainamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Procainamide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Propanalol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quinidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lidocaine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11880,"text":"Which of the following types of pericarditis is caused by Dressler syndrome?","explanation":"**Dressler syndrome**, also known as post-myocardial infarction syndrome, is characterized by **fibrinous pericarditis**. It occurs as an immune-mediated response a few weeks after a myocardial infarction.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 549.","responses":[{"text":"Purulent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemorrhagic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinous","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serous","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11881,"text":"What is the mechanism of action of nitrates?","explanation":"**Nitrates** such as nitroglycerin work by being converted to nitric oxide, which in turn activates **guanylate cyclase**. This leads to an increase in **cyclic guanosine monophosphate (cGMP)** levels. Elevated cGMP levels cause smooth muscle relaxation, leading to vasodilation.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 111.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibit cGMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activate cAMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibit cAMP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activate cGMP","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibit cAMP and cGMP","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11882,"text":"Which of the following is the acid used in vitriolage?","explanation":"**H2SO4** is also known as sulfuric acid. **Vitriolage** refers to the act of throwing acid, specifically sulfuric acid, on a person with the intent to disfigure or harm them.\r\n\r\nHClO4 (perchloric acid), HCl (hydrochloric acid), HBr (hydrobromic acid), and HNO3 (nitric acid)—are not commonly used for vitriolage.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 484.","responses":[{"text":"HClO4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HCl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HBr","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"H2SO4","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HNO3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11883,"text":"Where does papillary fibroelastoma occur?","explanation":"**Papillary fibroelastomas** are typically found in the ventricles **near the semilunar valves**. They are benign, avascular cardiac tumors that often resemble \"sea anemones\" and are typically attached to cardiac valves.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 576.","responses":[{"text":"Right atrium anterior wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricles near the semilunar valves","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right ventricle posterior wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left atrium anterior wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left ventricle near the apex","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11884,"text":"Which one of the following is the primary malignant tumor of the heart?","explanation":"**Angiosarcoma** is the most common **primary malignant tumor of the heart**. It often arises in the atria and can be particularly aggressive.\r\n\r\nFibrosarcoma is a malignant tumor but is not the most common primary malignant tumor of the heart. Lipoma, Myxoma, and Rhabdomyoma are all primarily benign tumors of the heart, not malignant.","reference":"Leja MJ, Shah DJ, Reardon MJ. Primary cardiac tumors. Tex Heart Inst J. 2011;38(3):261-262. Accessed June 22, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3113129/","responses":[{"text":"Angiosarcoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrosarcoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rhabdomyoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myxoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11885,"text":"A marble factory worker complains of cough and shortness of breath. He may have which of the following diseases?","explanation":"**Silicosis** is an occupational lung disease commonly seen in workers exposed to **silica dust**, which is prevalent in **marble factories**. Symptoms typically include cough and shortness of breath.\r\n\r\nThe other anwer choices pertain to different types of occupational lung diseases related to distinct exposures: berylliosis is linked to beryllium, anthracosis to coal dust, pneumoconiosis is a broad term for dust-related lung diseases, and bagassosis is associated with sugarcane byproducts.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 688.","responses":[{"text":"Silicosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumoconiosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anthracosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bagassosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Berylliosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11886,"text":"Hypothyroidism is associated with the prolonged use of which anti-arrhythmic agent?","explanation":"Prolonged use of **amiodarone** has been associated with thyroid dysfunction, including both hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism. This is largely due to the drug's high iodine content and its direct effects on the thyroid gland.\r\n\r\nProcainamide, lidocaine, propafenone, and flecainide are not commonly associated with hypothyroidism as a side effect during prolonged use.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 647-648.","responses":[{"text":"Amiodarone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Propafenone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flecainide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Procainamide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lidocaine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11887,"text":"An ethical review committee permission is necessary for most research studies. Which of the following research studies does not require permission?","explanation":"**Systematic reviews** involve the collation and analysis of **existing literature and data**, rather than direct interaction with human subjects or use of individual patient data that would necessitate ethical review. Therefore, they typically do not require ethical review committee permission.\r\n\r\nCohort prospective, cohort retrospective, case series, and cross-sectional studies all involve the collection and analysis of primary data, often from human subjects. These types of research usually require ethical review to ensure the safety, well-being, and privacy of the participants.","reference":"Suri H, Zawacki-Richter O, Kerres M, Bedenlier S, Bond M, Buntins K. Ethical considerations of conducting systematic reviews in educational research. Systematic Reviews in Educational Research: Methodology, Perspectives and Application. Published 2020. Accessed June 22, 2022. https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-658-27602-7_3","responses":[{"text":"Case series","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort - retrospective","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort - prospective","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cross-sectional study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic review","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11888,"text":"A patient has an abdominal aortic aneurysm that was found on abdominal examination. Aneurysms are dilation of blood vessels. Which of the following is true about aneurysms?","explanation":"True aneurysms involve all three layers of the arterial wall: the **intima, media**, and **adventitia**. This is in contrast to pseudoaneurysms, which do not involve all three layers.\r\n\r\nAneurysms can be either fusiform or saccular in shape; they are not limited to one shape. Aneurysms are not always congenital; they can also be acquired.","reference":"False aneurysm - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed June 22, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/pharmacology-toxicology-and-pharmaceutical-science/false-aneurysm","responses":[{"text":"They are always congenital","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are saccular in shape","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They involve the intima, media, and adventitia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"They involve the intima and media","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are fusiform in shape","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11889,"text":"Which of the following is a sublingual form of nitrate?","explanation":"**Glyceryl trinitrate** is the form of nitrate most commonly used **sublingually** for the immediate relief of **angina** symptoms. It acts quickly to dilate coronary arteries and improve blood flow to the heart muscle.\r\n\r\nAmyl nitrate, pentaerythritol tetranitrate, isosorbide mononitrate, and pentaglyceryl trinitrate are other types of nitrates, but they are not typically available in sublingual forms for the rapid treatment of angina.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 111.","responses":[{"text":"Isosorbide mononitrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glyceryl trinitrate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pentaerythritol tetranitrat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amyl nitrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pentaglyceryl trinitrate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11890,"text":"Which of the following is the best investigation for pericardial effusion?","explanation":"When suspecting **pericardial effusion**, **echocardiography** is generally considered the investigation of choice. It allows real-time visualization of the heart and surrounding structures, including the presence and extent of fluid in the pericardial sac. It's a non-invasive, quick, and highly sensitive and specific method for detecting pericardial effusion.\r\n\r\nCT and MRI can also detect pericardial effusion but are usually reserved for cases where echocardiography is inconclusive or additional anatomical detail is needed. ECG may show non-specific changes in pericardial effusion and is not diagnostic for the condition. CXR (chest X-ray) can indicate an enlarged cardiac silhouette in significant pericardial effusion but lacks the specificity and sensitivity of echocardiography.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 543.","responses":[{"text":"MRI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Echocardiography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"ECG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CXR","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CT","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11891,"text":"A 55-year-old male presents to the outpatient department (OPD) with abdominal discomfort and swelling of his legs for the past two years. On physical examination, jugular venous pressure is raised even when sitting up. The liver is enlarged and tender. Which of the following is most likely to cause these?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms, such as abdominal discomfort, leg swelling, raised jugular venous pressure, and enlarged, tender liver, are consistent with **right-sided heart failur**e. This condition leads to congestion of the systemic venous system, resulting in symptoms like **peripheral edema** and **hepatomegaly**. The **raised jugular venous pressure** is also a classic sign of right-sided heart failure.\r\n\r\nMyocarditis is an inflammation of the heart muscle that may lead to heart failure but is usually accompanied by other signs like fever and possibly a history of viral infection. Left-sided heart failure primarily manifests as pulmonary symptoms like dyspnea, rather than systemic congestion. Endocarditis involves inflammation of the heart valves and would be expected to show different symptoms, possibly including fever, heart murmurs, and other signs of infection. Myocardial infarction (heart attack) would typically present acutely with chest pain, and not the chronic symptoms described in this case.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 463.","responses":[{"text":"Myocardial infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right-sided heart failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Myocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endocarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left-sided heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11892,"text":"What is the recommended amount of exercise to prevent cardiovascular disease?","explanation":"According to the American Heart Association and other healthcare organizations, it is generally recommended that individuals engage in at least 150 minutes of **moderate-intensity exercise** per week to **prevent cardiovascular disease**. This translates to **30 minutes a day, 5 days a week**.\r\n\r\nWhile more exercise is generally beneficial, the 30-minute, 5 days/week regimen is often cited as the baseline for cardiovascular health.","reference":"Tian D, Meng J. Exercise for prevention and relief of cardiovascular disease: prognoses, mechanisms, and approaches. Oxidative Medicine and Cellular Longevity. Published April 9, 2019. Accessed June 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6481017/","responses":[{"text":"60 minutes, 5 days/week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"15 minutes, 5 days/week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20 minutes, 5 days/week","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"30 minutes, 5 days/week","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"10 minutes, 5 days/week","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11893,"text":"Which type of pulse is seen in cardiac tamponade?","explanation":"**Cardiac tamponade** is a medical emergency that occurs when fluid accumulates in the pericardial sac, exerting pressure on the heart and impairing its ability to fill and pump blood. **Pulsus paradoxus** is a specific type of pulse seen in this condition, characterized by a **significant drop in systolic blood pressure** during **inspiration**.\r\n\r\nPulsus parvus refers to a weak pulse with a small amplitude, and while it can be seen in various conditions, it is not specific to cardiac tamponade. Pulsus deficens is not a standard term used to describe a type of pulse. Pulsus alterans describes a pulse with alternating strong and weak beats, typically seen in heart failure with left ventricular dysfunction. Pulsus tremens is also not a standard term for describing pulse types.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 544.","responses":[{"text":"Pulsus deficens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulsus alterans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulsus paradoxus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulsus tremens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulsus parvus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11894,"text":"Which of the following has a decreased risk of cardiovascular disease?","explanation":"**Polyunsaturated fats** are known to decrease the risk of cardiovascular disease. They can lower levels of low-density lipoprotein (LDL), or \"bad cholesterol,\" which reduces the risk of **atherosclerosis** and cardiovascular events.\r\n\r\n\r\nAnimal fat, cheese, saturated fats, and butter are generally high in saturated fats and cholesterol. Consumption of these fats has been associated with an increased risk of cardiovascular disease, primarily due to their ability to elevate LDL cholesterol levels.","reference":"Ander BP, Dupasquier CM, Prociuk MA, Pierce GN. Polyunsaturated fatty acids and their effects on cardiovascular disease. Exp Clin Cardiol. 2003;8(4):164-172. Accessed June 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2719153/","responses":[{"text":"Animal fat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saturated fats","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cheese","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Butter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyunsaturated vegetable oil","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11895,"text":"What is the most prominent feature in rheumatic fever?","explanation":"**Migratory polyarthritis** is often the most prominent and commonly encountered feature in **rheumatic fever**. This form of arthritis usually involves large joints such as knees, ankles, elbows, and wrists, and it characteristically moves from one joint to another.  \r\n\r\nWhile erythema marginatum, pancarditis, Sydenham chorea, and subcutaneous nodules are all potential manifestations of rheumatic fever, they are generally less prominent than migratory polyarthritis. Erythema marginatum is a skin rash and is relatively rare. Pancarditis involves all layers of the heart but is not usually the most common manifestation. Sydenham chorea is a neurological symptom and is also less common. Subcutaneous nodules are firm, painless lumps under the skin but are also less frequently observed.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 515-516.","responses":[{"text":"Sydenham chorea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancarditis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subcutaneous nodules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythema marginatum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Migratory polyarthritis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12129,"text":"Which of the following properties enables the cardiac muscle to act as a syncytium?","explanation":"**Intercalated discs** are specialized cell-to-cell connections between cardiac muscle cells (cardiomyocytes). They contain **gap junctions** that allow for the rapid transmission of electrical impulses between adjacent cells. This property enables the cardiac muscle to function as a **syncytium**, where the entire myocardium contracts almost as a single unit.\r\n\r\nThe G protein is involved in signal transduction but does not facilitate the syncytial behavior of cardiac muscle. The sinoatrial node is the primary pacemaker of the heart and not a feature that allows muscle to act as a syncytium. The sarcoplasmic reticulum is involved in calcium storage and release but does not connect cells for coordinated contraction. The ryanodine receptor is a calcium channel found in the sarcoplasmic reticulum and plays a role in calcium-induced calcium release; however, it does not make the cardiac muscle act as a syncytium.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 113.","responses":[{"text":"Ryanodine receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intercalated disc","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sinoatrial node","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoplasmic reticulum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"G protein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12174,"text":"Hyperpolarization of the pacemaker potential is characterized by which of the following ion movements?","explanation":"**Hyperpolarization** of the pacemaker potential, such as in the sinoatrial node of the heart, is characterized by an **increased efflux of potassium ions (K+)**. During hyperpolarization, the interior of the cell becomes more negative, and this occurs when there is an increased outflow of potassium ions from the cell.\r\n\r\nThe efflux of sodium (Na+) would not lead to hyperpolarization; it typically occurs during the repolarization phase but is not responsible for making the membrane potential more negative. Similarly, an influx of potassium (K+), sodium (Na+), or calcium (Ca2+) would result in depolarization, making the membrane potential more positive, rather than causing hyperpolarization.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 132.","responses":[{"text":"Increased efflux for potassium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Influx of calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Efflux of sodium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Influx of potassium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Influx of sodium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14113,"text":"Which of the following can reduce the risk of sudden cardiac death in a patient with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Jameson JL, Fauci AS, Kasper DL, Hauser SL, Longo DL, Loscalzo J, eds. Harrison’s Principles of Internal Medicine. 20th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 1795-1796.","responses":[{"text":"Implantable cardioverter-defibrillator","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Radiofrequency ablation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"β-Adrenergic blocking agents","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular pacing","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alcohol septal ablation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14240,"text":"A 55-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with sudden onset of chest pain. An ECG shows ST-segment elevations in leads II, III, avF, V4, V5, and V6. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for this patient is **inferolateral myocardial infarction (MI)**. ST-segment elevations in leads **II, III, avF** (which represent the inferior wall of the heart), along with elevations in **V4, V5, and V6** (lateral wall), point to an infarction affecting both the inferior and lateral regions of the heart.\r\n\r\nAnterolateral MI would typically involve leads V1-V6, I, aVL, but not II, III, avF. Posterior wall MI often presents with ST-segment depression in the anterior leads (V1-V3) rather than elevation. Anteroseptal MI would primarily involve leads V1-V4, and an inferior wall MI would generally show changes in leads II, III, and avF but not the lateral leads.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 436.","responses":[{"text":"Anterolateral MI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferolateral MI","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inferior wall MI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anteroseptal MI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posterior wall MI","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14244,"text":"What medication should be avoided in a patient with both asthma and angina?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's medicine 24th edition, page 429","responses":[{"text":"Beta blockers","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Corticosteroids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium channel blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antihistamines","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14265,"text":"A 65-year-old man presents to the emergency department with sudden onset of chest pain radiating to his left arm. He is diaphoretic and short of breath. An ECG shows ST-segment elevation in the lateral leads. The patient is diagnosed with acute myocardial infarction involving the lateral wall. What is the most appropriate 'initial' management for this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Oxford handbook of emergency medicine, 5th edition, page 72 \u0026 75","responses":[{"text":"Percutaneous coronary intervention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinolytic therapy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Morphine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":14958,"text":"The modified Duke's criteria are used to classify the probability of infective endocarditis  (IE) as definitive or possible.  \r\nThe diagnosis of definitive IE according to Duke's criteria is made when which of the following options is fulfilled?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page no. 464","responses":[{"text":"≥ 1 major criterion PLUS ≥ 2 minor criteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"≥ 3 minor criteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"≥ 4 minor criteria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"≥ 2 major criteria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"≥ 1 major criterion PLUS ≥ 1 minor criterion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14959,"text":"Which of the following is the most common cause of dizziness in patients younger than 65 years?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 182.","responses":[{"text":"Anxiety","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasovagal syncope","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac syncope","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orthostatic hypotension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carotid sinus sensitivity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14960,"text":"Which of the following is the most common cause of syncope in the general population?","explanation":null,"reference":"Harrison’s Principles of Internal Medicine, 20th edition, page 123, 124.","responses":[{"text":"Vasovagal (Neurally mediated; reflex) syncope","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Micturition syncope","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac syncope","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Orthostatic hypotension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anxiety","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14981,"text":"A 64-year-old male with hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy and a previous history of MI presents to the clinic with a complaint of recurrent syncope. Echocardiogram shows an increase in left ventricular wall thickness from last year. \r\nWhich of the following is the most suitable option to prevent sudden cardiac death in this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidsons Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 475\r\nJameson JL, Fauci AS, Kasper DL, Hauser SL, Longo DL, Loscalzo J, eds. Harrison’s Principles of Internal Medicine. 20th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 1795-1796.","responses":[{"text":"Diltiazem","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Implantable cardioverter-defibrillator (ICD)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Digoxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"β-blockers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Septal ablation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":14983,"text":"Which of the following is the most common cause of sudden cardiac death?","explanation":null,"reference":"First Aid for the USMLE, Step 1, 2022, pages 310, 314","responses":[{"text":"Long QT syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe electrolyte abnormalities","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular tachycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ventricular fibrillation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15017,"text":"Which of the following is most appropriate for the treatment of bradycardia?","explanation":null,"reference":"Davidsons Principles and Practice of Medicine, 24th edition, page 223, 409, 420","responses":[{"text":"Intravenous atropine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous adenosine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous magnesium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Verapamil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pralidoxime","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

